+.. SPDX-License-Identifier: GPL-2.0
+
+========================================
+io_uring Latency Attribution with Tracing
+========================================
+
+The io_uring subsystem provides several tracepoints to help diagnose latency
+issues in high-performance applications such as deterministic accelerators,
+low-latency storage, and inference runtimes.
+
+Key Tracepoints
+---------------
+
+- ``io_uring_submit_req``: Called when an SQE is accepted from userspace.
+- ``io_uring_issue``: Called when the request is issued to the underlying op.
+- ``io_uring_complete``: Called when the completion is posted to the CQ.
+
+Latency Attribution
+-------------------
+
+By capturing the timestamps of these events for a specific request (identified
+by the ``req`` pointer or ``user_data``), you can compute the following:
+
+1. **Submission Delay**: ``t(issue) - t(submit)``
+   Time spent in the kernel submission queue, potentially waiting for a
+   worker thread or being deferred.
+
+2. **Execution Time**: ``t(complete) - t(issue)``
+   Time spent by the underlying operation (e.g., driver execution, compute).
+
+3. **Total Roundtrip**: ``t(complete) - t(submit)``
+   End-to-end latency from the perspective of the io_uring subsystem.
+
+Example with bpftrace
+---------------------
+
+The following bpftrace script calculates the execution time for requests:
+
+::
+
+  tracepoint:io_uring:io_uring_issue {
+      @start[args->req] = nsecs;
+  }
+
+  tracepoint:io_uring:io_uring_complete {
+      if (@start[args->req]) {
+          $lat = nsecs - @start[args->req];
+          @latency_ns = hist($lat);
+          delete(@start[args->req]);
+      }
+  }
+
+Fields captured
+---------------
+
+All three tracepoints capture the following common fields:
+
+- ``req``: The internal request pointer (stable identifier).
+- ``user_data``: The application-provided cookie.
+- ``opcode``: The operation code (e.g., IORING_OP_READ).
+- ``pid`` / ``tgid``: The task context.
+
